"Yes, Captain. You should be on your way by now, they were still in the mess hall picking up their rations."         Exactly at 0500, the Exodus Company gathered at the vehicle park. Shaw climbed onto a box and began to speak.
"We are being relocated to the forward operating base I-131, fifty miles outside of Ianlos. Our task is to support the ongoing siege and the subsequent attack on Ianlos in order to drive out the rebels. There we will establish a forward base at the foot of the mountains," explained Shaw. "Fall in with your squads and mount up."
The company broke up into their respective squads, and the soldiers were assigned by the sergeants to the tanks. Cohren climbed into one of the tanks further ahead in the convoy, where he met Nemic, Craith, and two new recruits. Cohren remembered the arrival of the two a few days earlier, but knew little about them. He sat on the side and let his legs dangle while he adjusted his backpack and the radio equipment, which was connected to his headset and throat microphone.
"Hey Cohren, is Snowball still with Harris?" asked Nemic after they had settled in.
"Do you mean the chicken he stole?" Cohren remembered the morning they had let the animal roam on a farm. "Yes, I think so."
Cohren looked over to one of the other tanks and spotted Harris with his squad. From the corner of his eye, he could see the movement of a small chicken searching the surroundings by constantly turning its head.
"Yes, he's still with him," answered Cohren as the tank's hatch opened and the commander came into view.
"All tanks, move out," spoke the commander slowly and calmly into his headset. The engines of the tank convoy and Stryker vehicles roared as they began to move. The Kronos tank Cohren was riding in shook as the brake was released and they joined the formation. The tanks moved in a wedge formation across the Itania plain. Despite the winter storms, the swamp areas were frozen and the forests were snow-covered, yet the mud was everywhere.
About an hour later, one of the recruits, whom Cohren knew was named Orson, began to speak. "Lieutenant, you've been here since the start of the war, right?"
"Yes, Operation Firestorm," answered Cohren. "We thought the matter would be resolved in a few weeks, but we underestimated it."
“Underestimated is strongly underestimated,” Nemic interjected into the conversation. “We were not prepared for their weapons arsenal and the number of soldiers. They destroyed the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks and only last month the Erebus. We should have even seen them on our way.”
“I stand firmly on the side of the Federation,” said Orson proudly. “I won’t let these terrorists scare me.”
“You say that now. But I saw that most of the eighteen-year-old recruits like you quickly take cover as soon as they hear a shot,” explained Craith.
“We’ll see about that,” said Cohren laughing. Orson ended the conversation.
“Exodus XO, Exodus CO,” crackled Cohren’s radio. “We are detecting heat signatures, about 300 meters away, 20 degrees to the right.”
Cohren climbed up on the tank and put on his specialty goggles. When he switched them to "thermal," he could see the signatures in the distance.
"Yes, I see them," answered Cohren over his throat microphone.
"Are they hostile?" asked the other recruit, Natayla.
"I can't tell," answered Cohren. He reached for his microphone and said: "Exodus Company, fire only when engaged. Let's lure them out."
As they approached, the point-like thermal signatures took shape. As they got closer, one of them ran off hastily to get something. Immediately, it returned to the small hill where the others were. The figures lay down on the ground, they went into firing position.
"We have enemy contact," Shaw shouted over the radio as orange tracer rounds were fired from the hill. While the tanks were under fire, the assault troops jumped down and took cover. A rocket streaked past and struck behind the formation, hitting the ground and exploding, scattering debris and rubble onto one of the tanks. Another hit the side of a Stryker, an APS-Cerberus, and exploded. The crew quickly climbed out and took cover as the ammunition exploded into the air.
"Iron 1-2 and 1-3, 25 degrees right, 300 meters. Fire," shouted the commander of the tank convoy over the radio. Iron 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire, grenades flying toward the hill and exploding, sending sludge and rock into the air.
"Send the Sentis in," called Knoxx, who was observing the hill with a binocular. The rear hatch of a Cerberus opened, and an unarmed soldier emerged, wearing a special headset. He gave orders into a square microphone, and two Sentis, officially called Sentinels, stormed out. Swinging their thin, metallic arms and legs forward, they burst into a sprint. They carried their weapons on their backs.
"Kill or capture?" asked Craith as they watched.
"It looks like capture," Cohren guessed as the two Sentinels disappeared into the ash and smoke cloud. Screams and gunfire echoed from the hill, but quickly faded. A short time later, the two Sentinels returned and dragged someone behind them, whose boots left tracks in the ground. After returning to the cover of the convoy, they threw the figure to the ground. She groaned in pain as she landed hard in the mud and snow.
Shaw went to the figure, who was just trying to stand up. Then he turned to one of the Sentinels. "How many?"
"Three dead, Sir," answered the Sentinel. "The rest fled on foot."
Shaw nodded and turned to Cohren and Craith, who were standing nearby. "Get this guy out of my sight!"
